(398, 1, '2020-12-01 06:24:26', '2020-12-01 06:24:26', '<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://scontent.fdvo1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.15752-9/128710096_379255110024646_2118184213167614898_n.png?_nc_cat=100&amp;ccb=2&amp;_nc_sid=ae9488&amp;_nc_eui2=AeEEwhPGgJNhvSPdOHIEXibH2kPILAhu2_baQ8gsCG7b9tz4sOooo9-KadLApA_kOtooW8XJomRxpZ5Yt3bVM1dh&amp;_nc_ohc=m6mcprvVuYIAX9HXXIr&amp;_nc_ht=scontent.fdvo1-1.fna&amp;oh=eca981ec6a2aa00f3600b8d0e3936c06&amp;oe=5FEA9F9A\" alt=\"No description available.\" />\r\n\r\n[soundcloud]https://soundcloud.com/emerginginnovations/episode-3-cacao[/soundcloud]\r\n\r\nWho would not love chocolates? With their delectable taste, chocolates have been everybody\'s favorite for thousands of years now.\r\n\r\nChocolate is a favorite food to millions of people on earth. However, have you asked yourself where chocolates come from? Or how chocolate is produced? Raw chocolate actually grows on a tree known as the cacao tree. Cacao is scientifically known as Theobroma cacao.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nDid you know that last September 7, 2020, the Department of Agriculture declared Davao City as the Cacao Capital of the Philippines? Yes! You heard that right!\r\n\r\nCacao is considered an equatorial crop- which means it thrives well in regions occupying the equator, that’s why the Philippines has a great potential in growing cacao considering our climatic conditions and soil characteristics here. That is our topic for this episode.\r\n\r\nWe will be highlighting a study from the University of Southeastern Philippines, a state university located at the heart of Davao City, Philippines. The study is “Physico-Chemical Characteristics of Soils under Cacao Production System in Davao de Oro, Philippines”.\r\n\r\nWe will learn directly from one of the proponents of this research, Mr. Nelvin A. Villason, a faculty of the University of Southeastern Philippines - Tagum Mabini Campus.\r\n\r\nIf you want to read more about this innovation, you may go to journal.usep.edu.ph and look for the paper titled “<a href=\"https://journal.usep.edu.ph/index.php/Southeastern_Philippines_Journal/article/view/75\">Physico-Chemical Characteristics of Soils under Cacao Production System in Davao de Oro, Philippines</a>”.', 'EMERGING INNOVATIONS EPISODE 3 - CACAO', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '362-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-12-01 06:24:26', '2020-12-01 06:24:26', '', 362, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2020/12/01/362-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(399, 1, '2020-12-01 06:24:41', '2020-12-01 06:24:41', '<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://scontent.fdvo1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.15752-9/128710096_379255110024646_2118184213167614898_n.png?_nc_cat=100&amp;ccb=2&amp;_nc_sid=ae9488&amp;_nc_eui2=AeEEwhPGgJNhvSPdOHIEXibH2kPILAhu2_baQ8gsCG7b9tz4sOooo9-KadLApA_kOtooW8XJomRxpZ5Yt3bVM1dh&amp;_nc_ohc=m6mcprvVuYIAX9HXXIr&amp;_nc_ht=scontent.fdvo1-1.fna&amp;oh=eca981ec6a2aa00f3600b8d0e3936c06&amp;oe=5FEA9F9A\" alt=\"No description available.\" />\r\n\r\n[soundcloud]https://soundcloud.com/emerginginnovations/episode-3-cacao[/soundcloud]\r\n\r\nWho would not love chocolates? With their delectable taste, chocolates have been everybody\'s favorite for thousands of years now.\r\n\r\nChocolate is a favorite food to millions of people on earth. However, have you asked yourself where chocolates come from? Or how chocolate is produced? Raw chocolate actually grows on a tree known as the cacao tree. Cacao is scientifically known as Theobroma cacao.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nDid you know that last September 7, 2020, the Department of Agriculture declared Davao City as the Cacao Capital of the Philippines? Yes! You heard that right!\r\n\r\nCacao is considered an equatorial crop- which means it thrives well in regions occupying the equator, that’s why the Philippines has a great potential in growing cacao considering our climatic conditions and soil characteristics here. That is our topic for this episode.\r\n\r\nWe will be highlighting a study from the University of Southeastern Philippines, a state university located at the heart of Davao City, Philippines. The study is “Physico-Chemical Characteristics of Soils under Cacao Production System in Davao de Oro, Philippines”.\r\n\r\nWe will learn directly from one of the proponents of this research, Mr. Nelvin A. Villason, a faculty of the University of Southeastern Philippines - Tagum Mabini Campus.\r\n\r\nIf you want to read more about this innovation, you may go to journal.usep.edu.ph and look for the paper titled “<a href=\"https://journal.usep.edu.ph/index.php/Southeastern_Philippines_Journal/article/view/75\">Physico-Chemical Characteristics of Soils under Cacao Production System in Davao de Oro, Philippines</a>”.', 'EMERGING INNOVATIONS EPISODE 3 - CACAO', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '362-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-12-01 06:24:41', '2020-12-01 06:24:41', '', 362, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2020/12/01/362-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(400, 1, '2020-12-01 06:25:34', '2020-12-01 06:25:34', '<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://scontent.fdvo1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.15752-9/128151516_412233219910051_3389996864896735926_n.png?_nc_cat=107&amp;ccb=2&amp;_nc_sid=ae9488&amp;_nc_eui2=AeFiyg0ct31Mt-ZIDhhWubA0H4_NJ_aK-rMfj80n9or6s6d8LmgQvDVBUx7MfNTV2sq4S6KyFq6vi-W-inTC3h8G&amp;_nc_ohc=EEPLS_VvOPMAX8niz2F&amp;_nc_ht=scontent.fdvo1-1.fna&amp;oh=535f65340b8df28771f002f63eda2274&amp;oe=5FEA7D9B\" alt=\"No description available.\" />\r\n\r\n[soundcloud]https://soundcloud.com/emerginginnovations/emerging-innovations-episode-1-rice-fish-farming-1[/soundcloud]\r\n\r\nHectares of paddy fields are the common scenery found in many parts of the Philippines! And for a farm, a farmer needs to invest about P35-50,000 per hectare which can earn P50-60,000 in four months.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nBut did you know that with tilapia farming, you can earn triple or more than one hectare of fishery, every four months? And because you can harvest three times a year, it is also a big help to sustain your rice field! This is the rice and fish farming crop diversification and that is what we are going to talk about today!\r\n\r\nFor this episode, we will be highlighting a study from the University of Southeastern Philippines, a state university located at the heart of Davao City, Philippines titled “<a href=\"https://journal.usep.edu.ph/index.php/Southeastern_Philippines_Journal/article/view/42\">A New Solar-Powered Rice-Fish Farming System for Yield Improvement</a>”.\r\n\r\nWe will be having one of the proponents of this scholarly innovation,  Engr. Ryan Abenoja, a faculty of the University of Southeastern Philippines -Tagum Mabini Campus. Let’s learn more from him regarding their innovation.', 'EMERGING INNOVATIONS EPISODE 1 - RICE FISH FARMING', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '295-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-12-01 06:25:34', '2020-12-01 06:25:34', '', 295, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2020/12/01/295-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(401, 1, '2020-12-01 06:28:41', '2020-12-01 06:28:41', '<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://scontent.fdvo1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.15752-9/127793290_413653606350196_6089789972757402675_n.png?_nc_cat=108&amp;ccb=2&amp;_nc_sid=ae9488&amp;_nc_eui2=AeERKXppJMx8mgj7BDtJZkQfrZNKyy_hhF6tk0rLL-GEXm4o1xh8xNL-98lofFff5tKw4ZiX13vG5mU_Vl5rDSgb&amp;_nc_ohc=z5X8UIUDAa8AX8WZXl0&amp;_nc_ht=scontent.fdvo1-1.fna&amp;oh=55e60e1c2574314583cb7154d1af94f7&amp;oe=5FEADC3A\" alt=\"No description available.\" />\r\n\r\n[soundcloud]https://soundcloud.com/emerginginnovations/emerging-innovations-episode-2-absorbent-polymers[/soundcloud]\r\n\r\nDid you know that water-absorbing Polymer can be used in growing bananas? Yes, Polymers! Farmers would not need to water the banana plant so often. Once watered, the Polymer will absorb the water and release it when the ground is dry. Interested to learn more? Well, this episode is for you.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nFor today’s episode, we will be highlighting a study from the University of Southeastern Philippines, a state university located at the heart of Davao City, Philippines titled “Application of Absorbent Polymer in Improving Water Use Efficiency and Growth Performance of ‘Lakatan’ Banana (musa sapientum l.) Under Nursery Condition”. We will learn directly from one of the proponents of this scholarly innovation, Engr. Ruel Tuyogon, a faculty of the University of Southeastern Philippines - Tagum Mabini Campus. Let’s learn more from him regarding their innovation.\r\n\r\nIf you want to read more about their innovation, you may go to the journal and look for their paper titled “<a href=\"https://journal.usep.edu.ph/index.php/Southeastern_Philippines_Journal/article/view/69\">Application of Absorbent Polymer in Improving Water Use Efficiency and Growth Performance of ‘Lakatan’ Banana (musa sapientum l.) Under Nursery Condition</a>”.', 'EMERGING INNOVATIONS EPISODE 2 - ABSORBENT POLYMERS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '318-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-12-01 06:28:41', '2020-12-01 06:28:41', '', 318, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2020/12/01/318-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
